<h1>Function Mnemonics </h1>
<p>
  Unlike the functions that are represented by single letters (like ppIt(f) or ppIt(W)) or perhaps 3 letter lowercase mnemonics (like exp, log, sin, cos, ...), this website uses a wide variety of two letter uppercase mnemonics. Here is a short explaination of each term, and a link to where to find more information about it.
  <ul>
  <table class="gloss" border="0px" cellspacing="5px" cellpadding="5px"><tbody>
  <tr><td><li>ppBi(AS)</li></td><td> Helm's ppEm(A)lternating ppEm(S)eries of ppGloss(tetrate)s.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><li>ppBi(DE)</li></td><td> a ppEm(D)ecremented ppEm(E)xponential function. See also ppGloss(decremented exponential)s.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><li>ppBi(EC)</li></td><td> the ppEm(E)xponential ppEm(C)ommutator. See also <a href="fn-expcom.html">here</a>.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><li>ppBi(EF)</li></td><td> the ppEm(E)xponential ppEm(F)actorial function. See also ppGloss(exponential factorial).</td></tr>
  <tr><td><li>ppBi(EG)</li></td><td> the ppEm(E)xponential ppEm(G)amma function. See also ppGloss(exponential factorial).</td></tr>
  <tr><td style="vertical-align: top;"><li>ppBi(H)</li></td><td> one of only 2 functions on this website to be special enough to have a single letter: the ppEm(H)yperpower function (coined by MacDonnell ppRef(M1)), now known as the ppGloss(infinite tetrate). Knoebel ppRef(K1), Galidakis ppRef(G1) and Corless et.al. ppRef(C1) all use ppV(h)(ppV(x)) to represent this function.</td></tr>
  <tr><td><li>ppBi(HF)</li></td><td> ppEm(F)rappier ppEm(H)yper-operators. See also <a href="hyper.html#frappier">here</a>.</td></tr>
